HW2 : Package Management on different OS

Summary:

In this assignment, I installed a few software packages on a few different operating systems.

OS Instances

The exercises below will be done once for each of the following operating systems/AMIs:

	"Getting Started on Fedora Core 8" (AMI Id: ami-b232d0db)
	"Ubuntu 9.10 Karmic Base" (AMI Id: ami-19a34270)
	a FreeBSD instance (AMI Id: ami-d560b7bc)
	a NetBSD instance (AMI Id: ami-2da67644 (note: type m1.large))

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

For "Getting Started on Fedora Core 8" (AMI Id: ami-b232d0db)

Creating the instance.

	1. Examine the AMI information.

		$ ec2-describe-images ami-b232d0db
		Unable to find a $JAVA_HOME at "/usr", continuing with system-provided Java...
		IMAGE	ami-b232d0db	amazon/getting-started-with-ebs-boot	amazon	available	public		i386	machine	aki-94c527fd	ari-96c527ff 	
		ebs 			
		paravirtual	xen
		BLOCKDEVICEMAPPING	/dev/sda1		snap-a08912c9	15

	2. Creating a security group.

		$ ec2-add-group cs615-hw2-group -d 'cs615 hw2 group'
		Unable to find a $JAVA_HOME at "/usr", continuing with system-provided Java...
		GROUP	sg-06bb766e	cs615-hw2-group	cs615 hw2 group

	3. Examining the group information.

		$ ec2-describe-group cs615-hw2-group
		Unable to find a $JAVA_HOME at "/usr", continuing with system-provided Java...
		GROUP	sg-06bb766e	496436440624	cs615-hw2-group	cs615 hw2 group	

	4. Adding a role for allowing user to access instance by SSH.

		$ ec2-authorize cs615-hw2-group -P tcp -p 22
		Unable to find a $JAVA_HOME at "/usr", continuing with system-provided Java...
		GROUP			cs615-hw2-group		
		PERMISSION		cs615-hw2-group	ALLOWS	tcp	22	22	FROM	CIDR	0.0.0.0/0	ingress

	5. Creating a key for accessing instance.

		5.1 Creating a key.

